 to the many new words needed to describe the full range of our emotional responses to the emergent state of the world. We need this creation of a hopeful vocabulary of positive emotions, argues Albrecht, so that we can extract ourselves out of environmental desolation and reignite our millennia-old biophilia-love of life-for our home planet. To do so, he proposes a dramatic change from the current human-dominated Anthropocene era to one that will be founded, materially, ethically, politically, and spiritually on the revolution in thinking being delivered by contemporary symbiotic science. Albrecht names this period the Symbiocene.With the current and coming generations, "Generation Symbiocene," Albrecht sees reason for optimism. The battle between the forces of destruction and the forces of creation will be won by Generation Symbiocene, and Earth Emotions presents an ethical and emotional odyssey for that victory.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aEmotionsxHealth aspects. 0aEnvironmentalismxPhilosophy. 0aHuman ecologyxPhilosophy. 0aNaturexEffect of human beings on. 4aEnvironmental History. 4aPhilosophy. 4aPsychology & Psychiatry. 7aNATURE / Environmental Conservation & Protection.2bisacsh  abiophilia.  aforces of creation.  ageneration symbiocene.  asolastalgia.  atopophilia.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311065198040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781501715242zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501715242423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781501715242.jpg  a978-3-11-065198-0  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019b2019  aGBV-deGruyter-alles